1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,371
Suppose you are listening to a program in English and hear the word “borrow.”

2
00:00:07,371 --> 00:00:13,157
You have heard this word many times but forget its meaning.

3
00:00:13,157 --> 00:00:18,827
So, you look up the equivalent word in your own language.

4
00:00:18,827 --> 00:00:22,973
Ahh, yes, now you remember!

5
00:00:22,973 --> 00:00:32,360
A few days later, you see the word again, but again cannot remember its meaning. Why?

6
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:38,528
It is easy to blame yourself or think, “I have a terrible memory!”

7
00:00:38,528 --> 00:00:41,845
But your memory is not the problem.

8
00:00:41,845 --> 00:00:53,883
The problem is that translating a word to its equivalent word in your language is not an effective way to learn vocabulary.

9
00:00:53,883 --> 00:01:04,536
This is because it does not create strong connections in the brain, something critical for remembering information.

10
00:01:04,536 --> 00:01:15,440
To really learn words, you have to bring attention to them and connect them with mental images or your existing knowledge.

11
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:21,840
This helps your brain recall words quickly and easily when you need them.

12
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:31,909
On today’s Education Tips, we will discuss three methods that use images to retain vocabulary.

13
00:01:31,909 --> 00:01:41,315
First, let’s discuss the most straightforward method: Using pictures as visual aids.

14
00:01:41,315 --> 00:01:47,419
Danielle Zelin is an English teacher and teacher trainer.

15
00:01:47,419 --> 00:01:59,251
She has taught for nearly 25 years, including in South Africa, Latvia and Mauritius, her homeland.

16
00:01:59,251 --> 00:02:08,725
Zelin says visual aids are important for language learners because humans think in images.

17
00:02:08,725 --> 00:02:27,301
“When we hear a sentence...[when] somebody is talking to us, we see the pictures. We don’t see the words. We don’t see the sentence in our brain. Like ‘Yesterday, I went to the beach.’ If I tell you that, you will see me on the beach. You will not see the sentence in written form.”

18
00:02:27,301 --> 00:02:36,213
She uses pictures or images with her beginning students and some of her mid-level students.

19
00:02:36,213 --> 00:02:48,307
Cristiane Galvão has used pictures to teach vocabulary to students of every level, from grade school to the university level.

20
00:02:48,307 --> 00:02:59,525
Galvão, who is based in California, has taught English for 20 years, including in the United States and Brazil.

21
00:02:59,525 --> 00:03:09,357
She suggests learners make visual dictionaries with pictures from the internet, for example.

22
00:03:09,357 --> 00:03:15,792
This would involve writing an English word next to its image.

23
00:03:15,792 --> 00:03:21,896
Before you make the dictionary, think about your goals, she says.

24
00:03:21,896 --> 00:03:33,480
If the goal is to reinforce what you already learned about, put the words in alphabetical order. And organize them into related groups.

25
00:03:33,480 --> 00:03:43,877
But if the goal is to write a sentence using each new word, then you probably do not need to put the words into groups.

26
00:03:43,877 --> 00:03:48,520
Next, let’s talk about mnemonics.

27
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:54,109
These are mental tools you can use to recall information better.

28
00:03:54,109 --> 00:04:02,304
Most mnemonics tools involve creating mental imagery to trigger your memory.

29
00:04:02,304 --> 00:04:09,245
Some of you have probably already done this without realizing there was a name for it.

30
00:04:09,245 --> 00:04:13,195
One great mnemonics tool is keywords.

31
00:04:13,195 --> 00:04:21,317
This involves making a mental image that ties two similar-sounding words together.

32
00:04:21,317 --> 00:04:28,973
Take the word “bald” as an example. It means having little or no hair.

33
00:04:28,973 --> 00:04:36,683
The word “ball” sounds like “bald” and can help us remember the target word.

34
00:04:36,683 --> 00:04:43,288
In your mind, make a mental picture of a ball with a face on it.

35
00:04:43,288 --> 00:04:50,336
Then, picture it with no hair on top, maybe a little on the sides.

36
00:04:50,336 --> 00:04:56,272
Keep this image in your mind for maybe 15 seconds.

37
00:04:56,272 --> 00:05:06,392
The next time you try to recall “bald,” it will be easier because of the keyword and connected imagery.

38
00:05:06,392 --> 00:05:14,728
Alex Mullen is a biomedical engineer and one of the world’s top memory competitors.

39
00:05:14,728 --> 00:05:20,829
In 2016, he was the USA Memory Champion.

40
00:05:20,829 --> 00:05:31,675
Mullen calls the mnemonics keywords tool “the art of memory” because your mind makes a kind of picture stories.

41
00:05:31,675 --> 00:05:44,627
In his video on mnemonics keywords, he talks about remembering the target word “corral” by joining its imagery with an image of a sea coral.

42
00:05:44,627 --> 00:05:51,731
He draws a group of stick figures trapped -- or corralled – in a coral.

43
00:05:51,731 --> 00:05:57,963
In real life, you would probably make a mental image rather than a drawing.

44
00:05:57,963 --> 00:06:06,917
But Mullen’s drawing demonstrates the idea of connecting a mental image of the target word with its keyword.

45
00:06:06,917 --> 00:06:15,293
One final method for today is word maps, also known as semantic maps or word webs.

46
00:06:15,293 --> 00:06:25,040
In a word map, you write a central word or idea in the middle and connect it with lines to related words.

47
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:31,877
This helps to build mental associations between related ideas.

48
00:06:31,877 --> 00:06:37,461
Danielle Zelin gives the example of the word “sharp.”

49
00:06:37,461 --> 00:06:48,107
If you center that word, you can connect it to words of things that are sharp, such as knife, paper and scissors.

50
00:06:48,107 --> 00:06:55,800
Zelin says words are much easier to remember when they have meaning in your own life.

51
00:06:55,800 --> 00:07:01,389
For instance, one of her French students has an English-speaking dentist.

52
00:07:01,389 --> 00:07:07,629
So, she learned words that she needed for her recent dental visit.

53
00:07:07,629 --> 00:07:13,843
Cristiane Galvão also says that context is important.

54
00:07:13,843 --> 00:07:23,576
She uses word maps in the classroom only after she has already discussed a subject and shown pictures.

55
00:07:23,576 --> 00:07:29,811
This makes the words meaningful before putting them into map form.

56
00:07:29,811 --> 00:07:37,848
Otherwise, she says, you are just reading and memorizing words, which is a bad idea.

57
00:07:37,848 --> 00:07:50,352
“Vocabulary is a big part of language learning. So, the more meaningful it is, the easier it is for the student to absorb.”

58
00:07:50,352 --> 00:07:55,955
Galvão says not every student will learn through a word map.

59
00:07:55,955 --> 00:08:03,123
But the maps can help you visualize and create a method that works for you.

60
00:08:03,123 --> 00:08:06,171
I’m Alice Bryant.